       Synthesis and characterization of isotopically labeled silver
       nanoparticles for tracing studies
       Laycock, Adam; Stolpe, Bjorn; Romer, Isabella; Dybowska, Agnieszka;
       Valsami-Jones, Eugenia; Lead, Jamie R.; Rehkamper, Mark
       Environmental Science: Nano (2014), 1 (3), 271-283CODEN: ESNNA4;
       ISSN:2051-8161. (Royal Society of Chemistry)
       Ag nanoparticles (AgNP) are ever-more being used in industrial
       processes and consumer products, resulting in increasing emissions
       to the environment. To understand AgNP behavior and environmental
       fate, it is paramount they can be traced in complex natural samples
       from exposure at high sensitivity. Stable isotope labeling is
       ideally suited for this purpose. To support such applications, a
       detailed evaluation of techniques to prep. stable isotope-labeled
       AgNP and demonstration that isotopically-modified particles are
       only distinguishable from particles with a natural isotope compn.
       by their strong isotopic signature, is presented. Monodisperse
       suspensions of citrate-stabilized AgNP of target sizes of 17, 20,
       and 30 nm were synthesized by reducing AgNO3 solns. with NaBH4.
       AgNP suspensions were produced using natural Ag, comprised of 2
       stable isotopes (107Ag [52%] and 109Ag [48%]), and Ag enriched to
       99.2% in 107Ag. Synthesis was reliably reproduced on 3 sep.
       occasions in 2 labs. AgNP were characterized by dynamic light
       scattering shortly after synthesis and after up to 12 mo storage.
       Some batches were also characterized by transmission electron
       microscopy and asym. flow field-flow fractionation. Particle size
       distributions showed good reproducibility between labs. and
       stability over 12 mo storage. 107Ag-enriched particles were
       indistinguishable in size and shape from particles with natural
       isotope compn. Reliability, particle size control, and high yield
       (∼80%) demonstrated the synthesis technique is well suited for
       small-scale prodn. of isotopically-labeled AgNP. Isotope mass
       balance calcns. showed the use of labeling enables AgNP tracing
       sensitivities which are at least 40 times, and possibly up to 4000
       times, higher than those achievable with bulk Ag concn.
       measurements, and expts. with exposure concns. approaching
       predicted environmental levels are possible, if the most precise
       isotopic measurement techniques are used.
