       Ecological uptake and depuration of carbon nanotubes by Lumbriculus
       variegatus
       Petersen, Elijah J.; Huang, Qingguo; Weber, Walter J., Jr.
       Environmental Health Perspectives (2008), 116 (4), 496-500CODEN:
       EVHPAZ; ISSN:0091-6765. (U. S. Department of Health and Human
       Services, Public Health Services)
       BACKGROUND: Carbon nanotubes represent a class of nanomaterials
       having broad application potentials and documented cellular uptake
       and ecotoxicol. effects that raise the possibility that they may
       bioaccumulate in living organisms. OBJECTIVES: Radioactively
       labeled nanotubes were synthesized using a novel methane chem.
       vapor deposition procedure. Single-walled carbon nanotubes (SWNTs),
       multiwalled carbon nanotubes (MWNTs), and pyrene were spiked to
       sediment samples, and the resp. uptake and depuration of these
       nanotubes and pyrene were assessed by the oligochaete, Lumbriculus
       variegatus. RESULTS: 14C-labeled carbon nanotubes were developed
       for these expts. to overcome significant previous limitations for
       quantifying nanotube materials in environmental and biol. media.
       Biota-sediment accumulation factors for SWNTs and MWNTs were obsd.
       to be almost an order of magnitude lower than those for pyrene, a
       four-ringed polycyclic arom. hydrocarbon (PAH). The depuration
       behaviors of the oligochaete suggested that the nanotubes detected
       in these organisms were assocd. with sediments remaining in the
       organism guts and not absorbed into cellular tissues as was the
       pyrene. The results suggest that, unlike PAHs, purified carbon
       nanotubes do not readily absorb into organism tissues.
