       Novel Characteristics of a Polystyrene Microsphere Prepared by
       Microemulsion Polymerization
       Ming, Weihua; Zhao, Jun; Lu, Xuliang; Wang, Changchun; Fu, Shoukuan
       Macromolecules (1996), 29 (24), 7678-7682CODEN: MAMOBX;
       ISSN:0024-9297. (American Chemical Society)
       Two kinds of styrene microemulsion systems were polymd. to prep.
       polystyrene microspheres (micro-PS), one emulsified by Na dodecyl
       sulfate (SDS) and coemulsified by 1-pentanol and the other
       emulsified by octylphenoxypoly(ethoxyethanol) (OP-10). Micro-PS
       possessed an essentially atactic configuration based on 1H-NMR
       measurement. Comparison of IR spectra showed some conformational
       differences between micro-PS and ordinary atactic PS (o-PS). Each
       polystyrene microsphere contains only about 3 macromol. chains
       (so-called pauci-chain microspheres), which adopt a special
       conformation: individual chains are highly compact, while the whole
       structure of the microsphere is relatively loose in comparison with
       a random-coil chain in a multichain system. There were apparent
       differences in thermal behaviors between micro-PS and o-PS during
       the DSC scan. Micro-PS displayed 2 exotherms near 107 and 157°
       during the first scan. In the subsequent scan, both exotherms
       disappeared and only one glass transition similar to o-PS was
       found. The first exotherm might be due to the sintering of
       polystyrene microspheres with small particle sizes. From wide-angle
       X-ray diffraction and polarizing optical microscopy studies, the
       second exotherm could be ascribed to the relatively compact
       conformation of polystyrene chains and the consequently formed
       slightly ordered regions inside micro-PS during the heating
       process. The special conformation was the driving force leading to
       its novel thermal behaviors. This is perhaps the first report that
       polystyrene from direct radical polymn. has the ability to form
       some kind of ordered structure.
