            14
            Tissue distribution and kinetics of dissolved and
            nanoparticulate silver in Iceland scallop (Chlamys islandica)
            Al-Sid-Cheikh, Maya; Rouleau, Claude; Pelletier, Emilien
            Marine Environmental Research (2013), 86 (), 21-28CODEN:
            MERSDW; ISSN:0141-1136. (Elsevier Ltd.)
            The fast expansion of the global nanotechnol. market entails a
            higher environmental and human exposure to nanomaterials. Ag
            nanoparticles (AgNP) are used for their antibacterial
            properties; however, their environmental fate is yet poorly
            understood. Iceland scallops (Chlamys islandica) were exposed
            for 12 h to 3 different Ag forms, dissolved Ag(I) (Agdiss),
            small (S-NP, Φ = 10-20 nm) and large AgNP (L-NP, Φ = 70-80
            nm), labeled with 110mAg, and bioaccumulation kinetics and
            tissue distribution using in vivo γ counting and whole-body
            autoradiog. were detd. All Ag forms were readily and rapidly
            accumulated. Elimination process was also fast and
            bi-exponential, with mean biol. half-life ranging from 1.4 to
            4.3 days and from 17 to 50 days for fast and slow
            compartments, resp. Most of the radioactivity concd. in the
            hepatopancreas. Agdiss and S-NP tissue distributions were
            similar indicating a rapid dissoln. of the latter in the
            tissues, contrarily to L-NP which appeared to form long
            lasting aggregates in the digestive system. Estd. steady-state
            bioconcn. factors (BCF), ranging between 2700 and 3800 mL g-1
            for dissolved and particulate silver forms, showed that C.
            islandica can accumulate significant quantities of Ag in a
            short time followed by an efficient depuration process.
