            Adherence of microplastics to soft tissue of mussels: A novel
            way to uptake microplastics beyond ingestion
            Kolandhasamy, Prabhu; Su, Lei; Li, Jiana; Qu, Xiaoyun; Jabeen,
            Khalida; Shi, Huahong
            Science of the Total Environment (2018), 610-611 (),
            635-640CODEN: STENDL; ISSN:0048-9697. (Elsevier B.V.)
            Microplastic pollution is recognized as an emerging threat to
            aquatic ecosystems. One of the main environmental risks
            assocd. with microplastics is their bioavailability to marine
            organisms. Up to date, ingestion has been widely accepted as
            the sole way for the animals to uptake microplastics.
            Nevertheless, microplastics have also been found in some
            organs which are not involved in the process of ingestion. The
            authors hypothesize that the animal might uptake microplastics
            through adherence in addn. to ingestion. To test this
            hypothesis, the authors collected mussels from the fishery
            farms, conducted exposure/clearance expts. and analyzed the
            accumulation of microplastics in specific organ of mussels.
            The authors' studies clearly showed the uptake of microplastic
            in multiple organs of mussels. In the field investigations,
            the authors found that the abundance of microplastic by wt.
            but not by individual showed significant difference among
            organs, and the intestine contained the highest level of
            microplastics (9.2 items/g). In the uptake and clearance
            expt., the accumulation and retention of microfibers could
            also be obsd. in all tested organs of mussels including foot
            and mantle. The authors' results strongly suggest that
            adherence rather than ingestion led to the accumulation of
            microplastics in those organs which are not involved in
            ingestion process. To the authors' best knowledge, it is the
            first time to propose that adherence is a novel way for
            animals to uptake microplastics beyond ingestion. This new
            finding makes the authors rethink about the bioavailability,
            accumulation and toxicity of microplastics to aquatic animals.
